<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96666784217632></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96666784217632><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=96666784217632>Blind kiting</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=96666784217632#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Sat, Aug 19th 2:50 AM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Good<span id=notbold>[3.81]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>I am supprised that noone has mentioned the shaman's "fear" kiting, using blind as an offensive spell.<br><br>Under 19 I always had blind memmed, it is a great offensive and defensive tool. <br><br>To blind kite, DoT a mob when sowed and head to a "pull spot", once in range reblind and dot as they run away, poison for this part. Then when blind wears off they come back and if the dot is gone, redot then blind again. If in melee range, step back a hair after the blind and the mob most of the time will start to run looking for you.<br><br>This works GREAT on melee type mobs.<br><br>As a defensive spell, should you get in trouble, root one, blind another, etc and you should be able to get away a lot of the time. My buddy stood over my shoulder one day at level 19 and watch a horde of 4 or 5 gnoll reavers descend upon me on a bad pull. SoW ran out and if it was my warrior at 19 or his ranger at 19, I would be dead. I managed to root or blind all of them, dump my mana in DD's on the one I pulled, loot it and make it to the zone. Blind has saved me many times and if you haven't gotten it, do so.<br><br>My favorite zone in the game for outdoor hunting from 14-29 is East Karanas, it is a gem of a zone for the soloing shaman and enough variety of mobs and levels to make you happy for a long time and use different spell tactics such as blind kiting, DoT and root, DD and kite, or debuff and melee. <br><br>Everytime you move from one zone to the next it often takes a bit of tinkering with the spell loads to find the most effective spells for each mob type. Some resist disease very well, unnerving when you first get scourge. Some resist cold amazingly well. Others are easy to melee even in the mid levels but give them some room and they will toast you fast with spells. For me learning what spells were the best for each mob was one of the biggest challenges I have found. Don't be afraid to experiment with new tactic ideas and try out different things, sometimes I never malise, other times I always open with malise, just depends upon the mob in front of me. I might root and dot with my pet on some but others I pet kite because I know my pet will die if I root and dot.<br><br>It changes with every mob and every spell circle. A word to the wise, when you get malise at 24 (I think that is right) it is useless until about 27 for soloing, just too expensive to recast if resisted and it WILL be resisted at times. But when it sticks, LOOK OUT! ;)<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
