<table  border=0 cellpadding=2 cellspacing=0 awidth=100%><a name=96662903217188></a><form action=http://eqdb.allakhazam.com/strategy/mrate.pl name=f96662903217188><tr><td id=headerrow><a id=sj href=classes.html?class=9&mid=96662903217188>Soloing a shaman</a> <a id=fs8 href=classes.html?class=9&mid=96662903217188#post><img src=http://everquest.allakhazam.com/static/reply.gif border=0 alt="Reply..." height=16 width=16></a></td><td align=right id=headerrow valign=bottom><span id=notbold>By:</span> <span id= >Anonymous</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=1 id=headerrow>Posted @ Fri, Aug 18th 4:03 PM 2000</td>
	   <td id=headerrow align=right><span id=notbold>Score</span>: Decent<span id=notbold>[3.33]</span></td></tr>
	   <tr><td colspan=2>Some of us actually don't group that much on EQ do to our schedule constraints.&nbsp;&nbsp;If you've picked a shaman as your character, then you've picked a good class to solo for a while. The only other class that I know make good soloers are Necromancers. A couple of notes if you choose to solo your shammy:<br><br>Kite Kite Kite:<br>For those of us who don't yet have Root but can cast SoW - cast a DoT from a distance and run.  Try keeping a 3rd person view (toggle the F9 key) so you can see how far back your opponent is before you stop to cast another DoT.  Don't forget to cast Drowsy on your opponent.  While it's not a root spell, it slows 'em down for both chasing you and hitting you.  Once you've stacked the DoT's it's time to stand and melee and cast.<br><br>If you are under level 9, your chances of being SoW'd by another character are very high if you do the following things: ask politely and in character, offer a donation up front.  You will find that many casters will SoW anyone who asks politely, and especially if you ask in character.  Also remember, the caster is using mana on YOU that they could be using on THEM, so giving a donation will make people a lot more willing to SoW you.  Personally, if someone offers me money to SoW them, I make sure I cast several buffs on them too.  Though never ever charge someone for a SoW who is on a corpse run.<br><br><br>For those of us that do have Root:  cast from a distance and make sure it hit.  If it didn't, cast again then stack your DoT's.  'Nuff said there.<br><br>Keep your skill level up in all weapons:<br>You never know when you'll come across a weapon better than the one you already have.  It really stinks to find a weapon with better stats you can use except for the fact that you're now medium to high level and you don't have any skills with the weapon.  <br><br>A word on Hand to Hand skills:  This becomes unimportant as soon as you reach level 9, as you can usually outrun your attackers using SoW.  However, for newbies past level 5 who now lose experience when they die, being able to fight without a weapon can make finding your corpse a lot easier and somewhat safer.  Always, no matter what level you are, have /loc and /corpse hotkeyed.  That way you can hit 1 key to get your location before you die to make it easier to find your corpse.  Use /corpse to drag your corpse to a save area whenever possible.<br><br>Getting experience:  Remember that killing things is not the only way to gain experience.  Follow QUESTS.  There are so many in the game that you can do that are still exciting no matter what level you are.  Performing quests is very important if you wish to level without grouping.<br><br>Grouping is a lot of fun, and can be very beneficial.  But it is unfair to group unless you have at minimum one hour to group.  Most players on Everquest do not group all the time or solo all the time, they do both.  There are many grouping guides, but not many solo guides other than how to kite.  <br><br>A note on timing for Groups: Two hours or more is much better for grouping.  And a note to all, use the /lfg on/off command!  It makes it much easier to find others to group with (especially if you don't keep /anon on while searching for a group- that way people know what level you are and that you want to group)<br>&nbsp;<br> </td></tr>
